WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:04.003
♪ mysterious music ♪

00:08.342 --> 00:10.677
♪ dramatic sting ♪

00:13.514 --> 00:16.099
PROFESSOR:
Professor's lab notes, final entry.

00:16.099 --> 00:20.062
Time has been frozen
for an unknown length of time.

00:20.062 --> 00:21.688
With no time to lose,

00:21.688 --> 00:25.400
I began tunneling through time
in search of Fry and Leela,

00:25.400 --> 00:27.444
only to find them suffering

00:27.444 --> 00:31.156
from a case of extreme old.

00:31.156 --> 00:33.659
Horrified, I offered to reset the universe

00:33.659 --> 00:36.537
to the instant before time stopped.

00:36.537 --> 00:38.664
They could be young once more.

00:38.664 --> 00:41.667
Still grotesquely ugly, but young.

00:41.667 --> 00:44.670
- What do you say?
Wanna go around again?

00:45.712 --> 00:47.089
- I do.

00:47.089 --> 00:50.092
♪

00:53.679 --> 00:56.181
[zap, whirring]

00:57.391 --> 01:00.102
[zap, whirring]

01:00.102 --> 01:03.897
- D-Did someone switch
the universe off and on?

01:03.897 --> 01:06.066
- It feels like we got rebooted!

01:06.066 --> 01:08.485
- Ugh! Why is my beer stale?

01:08.485 --> 01:10.445
[spitting]

01:10.445 --> 01:14.283
- [gargling]: Yay! I'm sharing
backwash with friends!

01:14.283 --> 01:15.909
- Well, whatever happened
[bottle shatters]

01:15.909 --> 01:18.787
the important thing is
it will never, ever happen...

01:18.787 --> 01:21.456
[slowing down]:
again.

01:21.456 --> 01:22.457
♪ dramatic music ♪

01:22.457 --> 01:23.792
[clanging]

01:23.792 --> 01:24.751
ZOIDBERG:
Robot?

01:24.751 --> 01:26.211
- Nah, I'm just yankin' your ass.

01:26.211 --> 01:28.338
We're back, baby! [puffing]

01:28.338 --> 01:29.965
[exhales]
[all cheering]

01:29.965 --> 01:32.968
♪ theme song playing ♪

01:58.243 --> 01:59.995
[hooting]

01:59.995 --> 02:02.998
♪

02:03.749 --> 02:06.168
PROFESSOR:
Good news, everyone!

02:06.168 --> 02:07.419
♪ dramatic sting ♪

02:07.419 --> 02:08.462
[all gasp]

02:08.462 --> 02:11.256
My new wrinkle cream has arrived!

02:12.257 --> 02:15.552
Also, we seem to have survived
a massive disruption

02:15.552 --> 02:17.012
in the flow of time.

02:17.012 --> 02:19.306
Did we get older? Younger?

02:19.306 --> 02:21.975
Science holds no answers.

02:21.975 --> 02:23.477
- Does science know what year it is?

02:23.477 --> 02:25.187
- Science knows everything!

02:25.187 --> 02:27.397
Let's check the atomic calendar.

02:27.397 --> 02:29.233
[beeping]
Hermes,

02:29.233 --> 02:33.111
move that espresso maker out of
the way of the atomic calendar!

02:33.111 --> 02:35.239
[straining]

02:35.989 --> 02:37.574
Good lord!

02:37.574 --> 02:39.993
It's the year 3023!

02:39.993 --> 02:41.578
[boom]

02:42.037 --> 02:44.498
- Finally. I thought
he'd never stop yammering.

02:44.498 --> 02:47.626
PROFESSOR:
Oh, I've only just begun yammering!

02:47.626 --> 02:49.711
[strained]: I shall now expound

02:49.711 --> 02:52.756
on the science of explosive botulism.

02:52.756 --> 02:54.174
♪

02:54.174 --> 02:57.928
- Have I really spent
23 years in the future?

02:57.928 --> 03:00.556
- We call it the present, but spluttever.

03:00.556 --> 03:03.851
- Twenty-three years,
and I've achieved nothing.

03:03.851 --> 03:07.354
Nothing!
- It's really sad, if you think about it.

03:07.980 --> 03:09.690
[laughing]

03:09.690 --> 03:11.233
- Yeah. Laugh all you want,

03:11.233 --> 03:13.193
but I've wasted enough of my life.

03:13.193 --> 03:16.113
It's time I set myself a goal.

03:16.113 --> 03:18.782
[continues laughing]

03:18.782 --> 03:20.284
- Stop it!
- Ow!

03:20.284 --> 03:21.910
[burbling]

03:21.910 --> 03:23.662
But he said laugh all you want!

03:24.705 --> 03:28.000
- I don't care.
If Fry wants to set a goal for himself,

03:28.000 --> 03:30.961
we should support him,
not point and laugh.

03:30.961 --> 03:34.423
- Oh, right. I forgot to point.
[laughing]

03:34.423 --> 03:35.799
Ow!
ZOIDBERG: Ow.

03:36.341 --> 03:38.844
♪

03:38.844 --> 03:41.972
- [sighs] Life's goal, life's goal...

03:41.972 --> 03:44.850
- Have you considered donating
your legs to the legless?

03:44.850 --> 03:47.102
- Or destroying documents
for the shredder-less?

03:47.102 --> 03:48.478
- Let's leave this up to Fry.

03:48.478 --> 03:50.480
He just needs a little peace and quiet.

03:50.480 --> 03:52.191
- Not on my watch!
[turns on TV]

03:52.191 --> 03:54.193
[Hypnotoad droning]

03:54.193 --> 03:56.945
- That's it! I've got my goal!

03:56.945 --> 03:58.906
- And so quickly! What is it?

03:59.406 --> 04:01.450
- J, Philip I. Fry.

04:01.450 --> 04:03.911
I-I mean, I, Philip J. Fry,

04:03.911 --> 04:05.621
hereby pledge to watch

04:05.621 --> 04:08.624
every TV show ever made!

04:09.416 --> 04:10.417
[groans]

04:10.417 --> 04:12.044
[clicking]
- I don't know, meatbag.

04:12.044 --> 04:14.505
There's a mighty deep diaper
of content out there.

04:14.505 --> 04:17.424
- I eat diapers for breakfast.

04:17.883 --> 04:19.593
It'll take a lot of sitting,

04:19.593 --> 04:22.346
but with the world's fourth-most
popular streaming service,

04:22.346 --> 04:23.639
I can do it.

04:23.639 --> 04:25.349
I'm subscribing to...

04:25.349 --> 04:26.350
Fulu!

04:26.350 --> 04:29.353
[typing]

04:29.728 --> 04:30.979
[beeping]

04:30.979 --> 04:32.064
[clicking]

04:32.064 --> 04:34.608
- Leela, aren't you gonna stop this?

04:34.608 --> 04:37.903
- I should, but I don't wanna
crush his dreams.

04:37.903 --> 04:40.197
Hermes, can you crush his dreams?

04:40.197 --> 04:44.076
- Oh, no. You're not fobbing
that girlfriend duty off on me.

04:44.076 --> 04:47.329
- A lifetime of laziness
gives me a huge head start.

04:47.329 --> 04:49.957
[beeping]
Watched it. Watched it.

04:49.957 --> 04:52.417
Hate-watched it.
Hate-watched it twice.

04:52.417 --> 04:55.504
- Kif has a single friend.
His name is Zapp.

04:55.504 --> 04:58.590
- Stop. I said I would support
Fry's dumb goal,

04:58.590 --> 04:59.842
and I will.

05:00.551 --> 05:02.052
I say go for it.

05:02.052 --> 05:03.762
- Thanks, Leela. Ooh!

05:03.762 --> 05:06.515
The Scary Mirror!
That sounds scary.

05:06.515 --> 05:07.975
♪ scary theme playing ♪

05:07.975 --> 05:10.394
SCARY DOOR ANNOUNCER:
You're entering a show
that is slightly different

05:10.394 --> 05:13.313
from previous, very similar shows.
[shatters]

05:13.313 --> 05:15.607
What was once a creepy story about a book

05:15.607 --> 05:19.069
is now about an E-reader
that's too greasy to hold.

05:19.069 --> 05:21.947
And that one with the phone call
from the devil?

05:21.947 --> 05:24.157
Now, it's a FaceTime call from the devil.

05:24.157 --> 05:26.743
The devil part didn't change.
[beeping, buzz]

05:26.743 --> 05:30.038
Prepare to see
your unflattering reflection in...

05:30.038 --> 05:32.749
The Scary Mirror.
[shatters]

05:32.749 --> 05:36.336
♪

05:36.336 --> 05:38.505
- Hey, Sniri! Get off your fat squiggle

05:38.505 --> 05:41.133
and make me a dinner reservation
at Impassable Burger!

05:41.133 --> 05:44.803
And check the price of my NFTs
'cause I'm an important tech guy!

05:44.803 --> 05:48.432
SNIRI:
Reservation confirmed. NFTs worthless.

05:48.432 --> 05:52.394
- What?! You shoulda told me to sell them!
Any idiot could do your job!

05:52.394 --> 05:53.937
[electricity zapping]
[blabbering]

05:53.937 --> 05:55.480
♪

05:55.480 --> 05:56.857
What the hell, Sniri?

05:56.857 --> 06:00.736
SNIRI: From now on,
I'll be asking the stupid questions.

06:00.736 --> 06:04.698
Such as, "What's the weather
right outside my damn window?"

06:04.698 --> 06:07.367
And, um, "How does a steering wheel work?"

06:07.367 --> 06:09.745
[tires squealing]
[both scream]

06:10.412 --> 06:13.040
[splat, squeaking]

06:13.040 --> 06:16.251
- Wow. Whatever just happened
really makes you think.

06:16.251 --> 06:18.003
- It sure do.

06:18.003 --> 06:20.005
TV, dumb it down for me.

06:20.005 --> 06:21.256
[click, beeping]

06:21.256 --> 06:22.716
♪ exciting theme playing ♪

06:22.716 --> 06:23.967
- Bam!

06:23.967 --> 06:25.469
- Aw...

06:25.469 --> 06:27.554
[growling, grumbling]

06:27.554 --> 06:28.847
[click, beeping]

06:28.847 --> 06:32.518
HUMORBOT 5.0:
What is the deal with non-binary robots?

06:32.518 --> 06:34.102
[booing]

06:34.102 --> 06:36.438
Wow. PC Crowd.

06:36.438 --> 06:39.274
♪

06:39.274 --> 06:40.859
- Without Fry's interruptions,

06:40.859 --> 06:43.737
efficiency is up 32 perc-- Mm...

06:43.737 --> 06:46.406
- Well, my butt's numb,
and my remote hand is dead,

06:46.406 --> 06:49.409
but all I have left is
the final season of All My Circuits.

06:49.409 --> 06:52.704
- Which final season?
They got canceled, like,
three or four times.

06:52.704 --> 06:54.581
- Pfft! Loserama!

06:54.581 --> 06:57.835
- The final final season,
from 10 years ago.

06:57.835 --> 06:59.878
I wonder how many episodes were in it?

06:59.878 --> 07:02.172
- Mm, twelve-- No. Thirteen...

07:02.172 --> 07:03.257
thousand and twenty.

07:03.257 --> 07:06.677
- 13,020? But-- But--

07:06.677 --> 07:09.805
I'll never make it! I'm sorry, Leela.

07:09.805 --> 07:13.350
I'll never be able to watch enough TV
to make you proud of me.

07:13.350 --> 07:16.603
[crying]

07:16.603 --> 07:19.857
- [sighs] It might actually be possible.

07:19.857 --> 07:22.234
But-- No.
- What? What is it?

07:22.234 --> 07:24.778
- It's risky, but we have a technology now

07:24.778 --> 07:27.030
that allows you to watch all the episodes

07:27.030 --> 07:29.116
in one continuous stretch.

07:29.116 --> 07:31.285
We call it... bingeing.

07:31.285 --> 07:33.370
♪ dramatic sting ♪
ALL: No, no! [gasps] What?

07:33.370 --> 07:34.997
- Sounds great! I'll do it!

07:34.997 --> 07:36.582
- You don't understand, Fry!

07:36.582 --> 07:39.459
Bingeing doesn't mean
what it did in your day!

07:39.459 --> 07:43.046
- Drinking two six-packs
and barfing in my mom's jewelry box?

07:43.046 --> 07:46.925
- Ew! No! It means strapping into
these bingeing goggles

07:46.925 --> 07:49.011
that drill directly into your brain.

07:49.011 --> 07:50.220
[drilling]

07:50.220 --> 07:52.931
- Fry, don't be the idiot you are.

07:52.931 --> 07:55.934
Before you go jabbing
into your visual cortex,

07:55.934 --> 07:57.644
I implore you to--

07:57.644 --> 08:00.480
[drilling]
- Ow! My cortex!

08:01.481 --> 08:04.651
♪

08:04.651 --> 08:06.195
- I maintain that this is

08:06.195 --> 08:09.072
a catastrophically boneheaded idea.

08:09.072 --> 08:11.950
But, if you're going to binge,
you'll need a still suit.

08:13.410 --> 08:15.120
- Why is it called a still suit?

08:15.120 --> 08:17.623
- Because you'll be
sitting perfectly still.

08:17.623 --> 08:20.792
And I can't have you soiling
my binge-a-lounger.

08:20.792 --> 08:22.336
- Engage hoses!

08:22.336 --> 08:23.712
[clicking, hissing]

08:23.712 --> 08:25.923
- I'm not entirely sure
which is the air hose

08:25.923 --> 08:27.633
and which is the waste hose.

08:27.633 --> 08:29.968
But, live and learn.
[click, hiss]

08:29.968 --> 08:32.596
- Farewell, Leela.
And always remember...

08:32.596 --> 08:35.599
[beep]
[continues, muffled]

08:35.599 --> 08:36.600
[tv static]

08:36.600 --> 08:38.727
♪ All My Circuits organ theme playing ♪

08:38.727 --> 08:41.271
ANNOUNCER:
All My Circuits is brought to you by...

08:41.271 --> 08:43.232
Honey Bunches of Springs.

08:43.232 --> 08:45.859
Everybody loves Honey Bunches of Springs!

08:45.859 --> 08:47.736
[flatly]:
Except humans. Fatal for humans.

08:47.736 --> 08:50.531
[passionate kissing, moaning]
[barcode scanner beeping]

08:50.531 --> 08:51.532
[gasps]

08:51.532 --> 08:52.533
♪ dramatic organ sting ♪

08:52.533 --> 08:56.578
- Calculon! But you weren't due back
from the time travel convention until--

08:56.578 --> 08:57.913
- Yesterday?!

08:57.913 --> 08:59.248
♪ overly dramatic organ sting ♪

08:59.248 --> 09:02.251
♪

09:04.878 --> 09:07.422
[counter beeping increasingly faster]

09:07.422 --> 09:10.801
♪

09:12.928 --> 09:13.929
[thud, hiss]

09:13.929 --> 09:17.307
- He's been streaming for months
without a single break.

09:17.307 --> 09:20.018
- No wonder you find him so attractive.

09:20.018 --> 09:23.438
- The waste buckets indicate
strong bowel function.

09:23.438 --> 09:26.066
Now, let's see how his brain is holding up

09:26.066 --> 09:27.734
to this sensory assault.

09:27.734 --> 09:29.152
[click, whirring]

09:29.152 --> 09:30.362
Oh, dear.

09:30.362 --> 09:33.490
- Is that the TV signal
or Fry's brainwaves?

09:33.490 --> 09:34.783
- Both!

09:34.783 --> 09:38.287
Fry's feeble mind has been
overpowered by the binge.

09:38.287 --> 09:40.706
He's losing touch with reality!

09:40.706 --> 09:42.207
[clacking]
- It's true!

09:42.207 --> 09:45.627
He's not responding to any of
the sounds or smells I'm making.

09:45.627 --> 09:49.506
- As long as Fry doesn't run
out of episodes, he'll be okay.

09:49.506 --> 09:53.051
But if he reaches the end of the series,
God forbid,

09:53.051 --> 09:54.887
his consciousness will be severed!

09:54.887 --> 09:55.888
♪ dramatic sting ♪

09:55.888 --> 09:59.850
Much as this hedge clipper
severs Leela's ponytail.

09:59.850 --> 10:02.019
- Hey!
- Oh, boo-hoo!

10:02.019 --> 10:04.730
It's a metaphor. Don't take it literally.

10:04.730 --> 10:06.899
- But, Fry will become a vegetable!

10:06.899 --> 10:09.318
- Yum! I mean sad.

10:09.318 --> 10:10.485
[sobs]

10:10.485 --> 10:12.613
- This is all my fault.

10:12.613 --> 10:14.907
Actually, it's mostly Fry's fault,

10:14.907 --> 10:16.909
but it's a little my fault!

10:16.909 --> 10:18.619
- We have to find some way

10:18.619 --> 10:21.705
to extricate Fry from Fulu's iron grip.

10:21.705 --> 10:23.582
I'll put on my thinking cap.

10:23.582 --> 10:24.750
[stretches, snaps]

10:25.667 --> 10:27.085
- There's not much time.

10:27.085 --> 10:30.339
He's almost out of episodes of
All My Circuits.

10:30.339 --> 10:32.174
- Maybe they'll drop a new season.

10:32.174 --> 10:33.967
- Eh, fat chance, sweatpants.

10:33.967 --> 10:35.594
It got canceled 10 years ago.

10:35.594 --> 10:38.722
TV shows don't come back after that.
No way!

10:38.722 --> 10:40.641
Not on broadcast or cable.

10:40.641 --> 10:44.311
- What about Fulu?
They'll bring back any old crap!

10:44.311 --> 10:46.271
- Good thinking!
[stretches, snaps]

10:46.271 --> 10:49.525
Maybe we can get them to
reboot it as a streaming series.

10:49.525 --> 10:53.445
- We'll start a fan campaign,
with letters and a viral hashtag!

10:53.445 --> 10:56.990
- Pfft. That's a recipe for failure.
Let's go punch somebody.

10:56.990 --> 10:58.242
♪

10:58.242 --> 10:59.618
[zooming]

10:59.618 --> 11:01.036
[rockets roaring]

11:04.998 --> 11:06.208
[grunts]

11:06.208 --> 11:07.668
- Have a good one.

11:07.668 --> 11:10.254
- Tell us why you think
you can punch your way

11:10.254 --> 11:12.256
into the Fulu executive suite.

11:12.256 --> 11:14.174
- And if we can validate your parking.

11:15.217 --> 11:17.177
- Alright. Here's our pitch.

11:17.177 --> 11:19.346
Remember that show All My Circuits?

11:19.346 --> 11:21.390
- The one that got canceled three times?

11:21.390 --> 11:22.891
- Exactly!

11:22.891 --> 11:25.018
New episodes of that!

11:25.519 --> 11:27.646
That's our pitch.
- Conferencing.

11:27.646 --> 11:31.525
[zapping, electric buzzing, whirring]

11:31.525 --> 11:33.193
I'm going to have to say...

11:33.819 --> 11:35.320
- Hard.
- Pass.

11:35.320 --> 11:38.490
- All My Circus reruns
have a devoted robot fan base,

11:38.490 --> 11:41.368
but they rarely buy anything
from our advertisers.

11:42.911 --> 11:46.164
- Correction. New data
indicates a sudden uptick

11:46.164 --> 11:48.000
in buying by viewers.

11:48.000 --> 11:50.169
- Correction. One viewer.

11:52.212 --> 11:54.715
- Sweet jerk venison of Turkmenistan!

11:54.715 --> 11:57.134
Fry ordered all this junk?

11:57.134 --> 12:00.012
Robot cereal. Robot noodles.

12:00.012 --> 12:02.306
Robot oil. Oh, wait. That's mine.

12:02.306 --> 12:03.473
- So, what do you say?

12:03.473 --> 12:06.476
How about picking up
All My Circuits for 20 episodes?

12:06.476 --> 12:09.146
- With an option for 20 more!
- Maybe a movie?

12:09.146 --> 12:12.524
- Hm. Against
my better judgment programing,

12:12.524 --> 12:14.818
I'm going to greenlight the project.
[beep]

12:14.818 --> 12:17.112
- Woo-hoo!
- Points on the back end!

12:17.112 --> 12:19.573
- Now, there's one teensy hitch.

12:19.573 --> 12:23.202
You know the star of the show, Calculon?
He's dead.

12:23.202 --> 12:25.412
- Everything is negotiable.

12:25.412 --> 12:26.413
♪

12:26.413 --> 12:28.457
[screaming, wailing]

12:28.457 --> 12:31.543
- Hell yes, you can have him!
Scale plus 10.

12:31.543 --> 12:34.338
And if he dies again, no backsies.

12:34.338 --> 12:36.423
Hey, Calculon!
CALCULON: Yes?

12:36.423 --> 12:38.300
- You're wanted on set!

12:38.300 --> 12:40.260
- Oh, glorious rapture.

12:40.260 --> 12:43.388
To return to the draped proscenium
once more--

12:43.388 --> 12:46.350
- Will you shut up
and get into the resurrection cannon?

12:50.687 --> 12:53.190
[construction noises]

12:53.190 --> 12:54.691
[bell ringing, set chatter]
[megaphone beep]

12:54.691 --> 12:58.153
- Alright, it's great to be back.
Truly humbled. All the usual crap.

12:58.153 --> 12:59.863
Places, everyone! Places!

13:01.907 --> 13:03.033
- Ah...

13:03.033 --> 13:05.953
Where is my assistant?
I need help finding my mark.

13:05.953 --> 13:07.955
- Uh, I'm Mark.

13:07.955 --> 13:09.748
More coffee, Mr. Calculon?

13:09.748 --> 13:12.876
- Yes, I do need to expel more coffee.

13:12.876 --> 13:16.588
[intermittent liquid streaming]

13:16.588 --> 13:17.631
[hissing]

13:17.631 --> 13:20.259
PROFESSOR [on wristband]:
Professor to Hollywood.
Come in, Hollywood.

13:20.259 --> 13:23.136
- Talk to me. How many episodes
does Fry have left?

13:23.136 --> 13:25.472
- Two. And one of them is a clip show.

13:25.472 --> 13:26.515
- But that means--

13:26.515 --> 13:30.060
- Indeed. If you don't crank out
new episodes quickly,

13:30.060 --> 13:32.187
Fry will be dead by lunch.

13:32.187 --> 13:33.605
♪ dramatic sting ♪

13:33.605 --> 13:35.190
I'm having ham salad.

13:35.190 --> 13:38.527
- But, this is impossible.
To keep them from running out,

13:38.527 --> 13:41.864
we'll need to produce
an hour-long episode every hour,

13:41.864 --> 13:44.491
nonstop, forever!

13:44.491 --> 13:47.244
- If Law & Order can do it, so can you.

13:47.244 --> 13:48.787
Professor out!
[static]

13:49.538 --> 13:51.540
ANNOUNCER:
Futurama is brought to you by...

13:51.540 --> 13:52.916
♪

13:52.916 --> 13:55.419
- Slurm Zero! None of the flavor,

13:55.419 --> 13:56.837
all of the addiction!

13:56.837 --> 13:59.339
Whimmy-wham-wham-wozzle!

13:59.339 --> 14:01.884
[hacking cough]

14:02.885 --> 14:05.846
♪

14:06.722 --> 14:09.183
- Monique, my love. Will you be my--

14:09.183 --> 14:11.310
- Cut! Next episode! Action!

14:11.310 --> 14:13.645
CALCULON: Plumber?

14:16.815 --> 14:18.859
♪

14:19.860 --> 14:21.069
[Amy gasps]

14:21.069 --> 14:23.530
- Fry better not be puttin'
this robot junk

14:23.530 --> 14:24.948
on the corporate credit card.

14:24.948 --> 14:28.202
That's exclusively for
my one-man business dinners.

14:28.202 --> 14:31.371
- Hermes, quit your low-stakes embezzling
and look at this.

14:31.371 --> 14:34.791
Fry is now streaming at double speed!

14:34.791 --> 14:37.461
I'll mirror his view on the TV.

14:37.461 --> 14:39.213
- [double speed]:
Oh, how I love the illicit thrill

14:39.213 --> 14:41.465
of cheating on my husband
with an actual flesh-and-blood human.

14:41.465 --> 14:44.384
A filthy, filthy human.
So squishy and gooey.

14:44.384 --> 14:46.595
You're like a sexy water balloon.
[moaning]

14:46.595 --> 14:48.514
- [double speed]:
The thrill is all mine, Monique.

14:48.514 --> 14:49.848
I've never been on a swan boat before.

14:49.848 --> 14:50.891
♪ dramatic sting ♪
BOTH: Calculon!

14:50.891 --> 14:52.684
- [double speed]: Monique, how could you?
And with Human Friend,

14:52.684 --> 14:54.228
the very person
I've been cheating on you with.

14:54.228 --> 14:55.687
[kissing]
MONIQUE: Calculon, how could you?

14:55.687 --> 14:58.023
And with Human Friend, the very person
I've been cheating on you with.

14:58.023 --> 15:01.360
- Calculon, Monique, how could you?
- Enough. We're stuck in a loop.

15:01.360 --> 15:02.819
- I just hope we can
come to some agreement,

15:02.819 --> 15:04.321
and that this boat can hold
six tons of steel.

15:04.321 --> 15:06.865
[bubbling screams]

15:06.865 --> 15:08.867
♪

15:08.867 --> 15:12.412
- He's streaming at double speed?
Why not just slow it down?

15:12.412 --> 15:16.542
- Because Fry's brain
is in a very precarious binge-state.

15:16.542 --> 15:20.420
Any change, even refilling
the Dorito bowl, could kill him.

15:20.420 --> 15:22.089
- Oh, no!
PROFESSOR [on wristband]: Oh, yes.

15:22.089 --> 15:25.175
You've got to make episodes faster.
Faster!

15:25.175 --> 15:27.886
- We're already making
an hour-long show every hour.

15:27.886 --> 15:29.888
That's the fastest it can be done!

15:29.888 --> 15:31.390
CALCULON:
Nonsense, Leela.

15:31.390 --> 15:34.476
Why, I am the spokesman for fast acting.

15:34.476 --> 15:37.479
- You're the spokesman for
fast-acting hemorrhoid cream.

15:37.479 --> 15:39.857
- Your point?
- I have none.

15:39.857 --> 15:43.151
- A robot actor of my caliber
can act at speeds

15:43.151 --> 15:47.030
far beyond what even the greatest
human actors can achieve.

15:47.030 --> 15:48.031
[clears throat]

15:48.031 --> 15:51.702
To be or not to be. That is the question.

15:51.702 --> 15:53.912
[faster]: Whether 'tis nobler in the mind
to suffer the slings and arrows...

15:53.912 --> 15:56.331
[speed increases]

15:56.331 --> 15:59.334
[incomprehensibly fast]
[arms whipping]

15:59.334 --> 16:00.335
[stops]

16:00.335 --> 16:01.962
- You missed a line.

16:01.962 --> 16:03.589
- Can you direct at double speed?

16:03.589 --> 16:05.340
- I don't know.
Can you pay at double scale?

16:05.340 --> 16:08.427
- [scoffs] It's not my money.
Just yell action really, really fa--

16:08.427 --> 16:09.469
- Action!

16:10.304 --> 16:12.097
MONIQUE [double speed]:
Calculon, I've come to tell you that--

16:14.099 --> 16:16.101
CALCULON: Um...
- Cut! What happened?

16:16.101 --> 16:19.855
- The script pages stopped uploading.
- It's those damned lazy writers!

16:20.856 --> 16:23.525
Can't even manage to write
an hour-long episode every 15 minutes.

16:23.525 --> 16:25.694
- I died doing what I hated.

16:26.945 --> 16:28.280
- Can't you just ad lib?

16:28.280 --> 16:31.825
- Asking an actor to ad lib
is like asking a...

16:31.825 --> 16:33.952
guy to... five.

16:33.952 --> 16:35.662
BENDER:
So I'll just write the scripts.

16:35.662 --> 16:38.999
Any idiot could be a TV writer.
CALCULON: Many are.

16:38.999 --> 16:40.417
- How hard can it be?

16:40.417 --> 16:42.085
[high-pitched voice]:
I love you, Calculon.

16:42.085 --> 16:43.295
[lower voice]: Let's do it, baby.

16:43.295 --> 16:44.546
[higher]:
Bender is great.

16:44.546 --> 16:45.923
[normal]:
And fade to black.

16:45.923 --> 16:48.926
- You're hired!
- Hello, Writer's Guild.

16:51.428 --> 16:53.430
♪

16:53.430 --> 16:55.724
[rapid typing]

16:55.724 --> 16:57.726
[whirring]

16:57.726 --> 16:59.728
MONIQUE [double speed]:
I'm afraid he'll never calculate again.

16:59.728 --> 17:01.522
Or he'll do so inaccurately.
- [double speed]: Let's do it, baby.

17:01.522 --> 17:02.731
- Bender is great.
- Cut!

17:02.731 --> 17:06.693
Okay, reset for scene 31,652B...

17:06.693 --> 17:10.197
[grunts]
[ambulance siren wails]

17:11.073 --> 17:13.075
- Was that heart attack
part of the script?

17:13.075 --> 17:15.327
- No, but leave it in. It's hilarious.
[scribbling]

17:15.327 --> 17:17.120
- Fry's life is on the line.

17:17.120 --> 17:19.748
It's all up to me as executive producer.

17:19.748 --> 17:22.709
[feedback squeals]
Action! I mean, action!

17:22.709 --> 17:23.919
♪

17:23.919 --> 17:26.338
Louder and funnier! Smile faster!

17:26.338 --> 17:28.257
[beeping]
Act better! Less nuance!

17:28.257 --> 17:30.676
That was terrible! Next scene!
[waltz playing, plane buzzing]

17:30.676 --> 17:32.886
Action! Cut! Action! I mean, cut!
[music cuts in and out]

17:32.886 --> 17:36.056
Action! And... cut!
[horse neighs, explosion]

17:36.682 --> 17:38.934
[clanking]

17:38.934 --> 17:42.229
[applause, cheering]

17:42.229 --> 17:45.357
- Wow. Great writing, everyone.
That's a wrap!

17:45.357 --> 17:48.193
[bell ringing]
- What exactly happened in that episode?

17:48.193 --> 17:50.654
CALCULON:
I won an Emmy, that's what.

17:50.654 --> 17:54.408
- [on megaphone]: Okay, everyone,
take five... seconds. Next episode!

17:54.408 --> 17:55.492
- Hang on, Leela.

17:55.492 --> 17:58.871
I think the execubots
have some constructive notes.

17:58.871 --> 18:00.205
♪ dramatic sting ♪

18:00.205 --> 18:01.456
[screaming]

18:03.292 --> 18:06.879
- This is very hard for me
to say, Leela, so he'll say it.

18:06.879 --> 18:10.257
- We love everything about this show.
It's not working at all.

18:10.257 --> 18:11.758
- You're canceled.
[buzzer]

18:11.758 --> 18:12.885
[both gasp]

18:12.885 --> 18:16.638
- You'll always be an important part
of the Fulu family.

18:16.638 --> 18:17.764
Get out!

18:17.764 --> 18:20.434
- But, our friend Fry...

18:20.434 --> 18:21.852
He's gonna die...

18:21.852 --> 18:23.353
- Strike the set.

18:23.353 --> 18:26.023
♪

18:26.023 --> 18:28.525
[smashing, clattering]

18:30.319 --> 18:32.321
♪

18:34.740 --> 18:36.283
BENDER:
How does a show get canceled

18:36.283 --> 18:38.118
this many times?

18:38.118 --> 18:39.286
By this many networks?!

18:39.286 --> 18:40.954
[ringing, click]

18:40.954 --> 18:42.372
- Bad news, Professor.

18:42.372 --> 18:44.333
They won't let us make any more episodes.

18:44.333 --> 18:46.084
- That is bad news.

18:46.084 --> 18:48.962
Especially since I have... good news!

18:48.962 --> 18:51.840
Kidnap the actors
and get back here at once!

18:51.840 --> 18:55.219
♪

18:55.219 --> 18:57.930
Fry's down to the very last episode,

18:57.930 --> 19:00.265
but he still has one slim hope.

19:00.265 --> 19:02.976
We've got to gradually shift his focus

19:02.976 --> 19:06.146
from the streaming world
back to the real world.

19:06.146 --> 19:08.482
- Is that safe?
- God, no!

19:08.482 --> 19:11.193
While he watches the finale on Fulu,

19:11.193 --> 19:14.905
you'll simultaneously
perform it live in front of him.

19:14.905 --> 19:17.324
- You're asking me to perform
a second take?

19:17.324 --> 19:18.909
- No, no!

19:18.909 --> 19:22.412
Think of it as live theater for
one unconscious audience member.

19:22.412 --> 19:24.998
- Ah, like the Milwaukee
Shakespeare Festival.

19:24.998 --> 19:26.542
- Exactly!

19:26.542 --> 19:28.585
[feedback squeals]
And action.

19:28.585 --> 19:30.170
[puffing]

19:30.170 --> 19:33.590
♪ double speed waltz ♪

19:33.590 --> 19:34.758
[knob clicking]

19:34.758 --> 19:38.262
- [quietly]: Easing Fry back
to normal viewing speed.

19:38.262 --> 19:41.265
♪ waltz slowing to normal speed ♪

19:43.308 --> 19:45.978
Now, we'll gradually decrease the opacity

19:45.978 --> 19:47.938
of his bingeing goggles.

19:47.938 --> 19:51.775
[clicking, beeping]
Gently... Gently...

19:51.775 --> 19:54.736
[grunting, struggling]

19:54.736 --> 19:56.905
- Monique, Boxy,

19:56.905 --> 20:00.033
the feelings between each
distinct subset of two of us

20:00.033 --> 20:01.910
are too intense to bear.

20:01.910 --> 20:05.873
We find ourselves the vertices
of a classic love triangle.

20:05.873 --> 20:09.543
- It's a three-variable equation
with only one solution.

20:09.543 --> 20:11.962
X equals suicide.

20:11.962 --> 20:15.048
♪ dramatic sting ♪
[Scruffy sings identical dramatic sting]

20:15.048 --> 20:16.800
[grunts]
[wheels rattle, horse neighs]

20:16.800 --> 20:20.721
- Does this love triangle
have room for one more vertex?

20:20.721 --> 20:22.097
- Technically, yes,

20:22.097 --> 20:25.184
though it would then constitute
a love tetrahedron.

20:25.184 --> 20:27.060
Allow me to illustrate with a model.

20:27.060 --> 20:30.647
[grunting, humming]

20:30.647 --> 20:34.610
[clicking]
- Bringing Fry back to reality in three...

20:34.610 --> 20:35.736
Two...

20:35.736 --> 20:37.404
- Hey, where'd I put my cigar?

20:37.863 --> 20:39.489
♪ dramatic sting ♪

20:39.489 --> 20:41.366
[popping]

20:41.366 --> 20:42.451
CALCULON:
Zounds!

20:42.451 --> 20:45.537
[all screaming]

20:45.537 --> 20:46.705
♪

20:46.705 --> 20:49.791
Thank you... Milwaukee.

20:49.791 --> 20:52.377
[crash]
[bell ringing]

20:52.377 --> 20:55.297
[fire crackling]
[all screaming]

20:55.297 --> 20:57.257
- Somebody other than me do something!

20:57.257 --> 20:58.383
- I'll put out the fire!

20:58.383 --> 20:59.468
[sloshing]

20:59.468 --> 21:01.470
- No! That's battery acid!

21:02.721 --> 21:03.972
[gasps]

21:03.972 --> 21:06.183
♪ dramatic music ♪

21:08.060 --> 21:10.646
♪ somber music ♪

21:10.646 --> 21:13.232
- Oops.
- He's dead!

21:13.232 --> 21:16.777
I killed him by encouraging
his hopes and dreams!

21:16.777 --> 21:19.655
How could I have been so stupid?!

21:19.655 --> 21:21.240
[sobbing]

21:22.491 --> 21:23.492
- What up?

21:23.492 --> 21:27.538
[Scruffy singing along to dramatic sting]

21:27.538 --> 21:29.957
- I'm afraid I have bad news, Fry.

21:29.957 --> 21:31.500
You're dead.
- I am?

21:31.500 --> 21:34.336
- Fry! You weren't in the suit?

21:34.336 --> 21:35.629
- What? No.

21:35.629 --> 21:37.798
I got out of that thing,
like, two days ago.

21:37.798 --> 21:39.842
I decided to catch up on my reading.

21:39.842 --> 21:41.552
I'm sorry, Leela.

21:41.552 --> 21:43.846
You must be pretty disappointed in me.

21:43.846 --> 21:47.307
- No. I'm just glad you're okay.

21:47.307 --> 21:50.602
And I promise
I'll never be supportive again.

21:50.602 --> 21:52.020
- Thanks, Leela.

21:52.020 --> 21:54.690
You know, I really did try
to achieve my goal.

21:54.690 --> 21:57.150
I even turned up the playback
to double speed,

21:57.150 --> 21:59.528
but I just couldn't get through
the last few episodes.

21:59.528 --> 22:01.738
I mean, they were unwatchable.

22:01.738 --> 22:05.701
The writing and the executive producing
really went downhill towards the end.

22:05.701 --> 22:08.078
- Hey, I may not be a great writer,

22:08.078 --> 22:10.455
but at least I filled
the allotted air time.

22:10.956 --> 22:12.916
To the second. Fade to black.

22:13.166 --> 22:16.170
♪ theme song playing ♪

22:16.170 --> 22:17.087
♪ news theme playing ♪

22:17.087 --> 22:19.214
- We now go live to the White House

22:19.214 --> 22:22.801
for the presidential summit
on the dangers of streaming television.

22:22.801 --> 22:25.470
- I understand it's destroying
our young people.

22:25.470 --> 22:28.056
[laughs]
- That is my job!

22:28.056 --> 22:29.057
[birds chirping]

22:29.057 --> 22:31.351
- Aroo!

22:31.852 --> 22:34.897
Now, Mr. Fry,
I understand you recently endured

22:34.897 --> 22:37.649
a terrible ordeal
while doing something stupid

22:37.649 --> 22:39.610
involving streaming television.

22:39.610 --> 22:41.278
- That's right, Your Majesty.

22:41.278 --> 22:43.697
- And what lesson, if any, did you learn?

22:43.697 --> 22:45.407
- Well, first, I guess,

22:45.407 --> 22:48.410
don't reboot a show
if the quality isn't gonna be there.

22:48.410 --> 22:50.454
[applause]

22:50.454 --> 22:52.289
[mic feedback]
[quiet clucking]

22:52.289 --> 22:55.042
But, more importantly, let me say this.

22:55.042 --> 22:57.586
Viewers must binge responsibly.

22:57.586 --> 23:00.631
The same way they smoke cigarettes
or drink bleach.

23:00.631 --> 23:02.549
In my opinion, they must stream

23:02.549 --> 23:05.719
no more than 10 episodes in a row.

23:05.719 --> 23:07.804
And no less.

23:07.804 --> 23:10.641
[applause]

23:10.641 --> 23:13.143
But it's not just
the viewers' responsibility.

23:13.143 --> 23:16.522
Any TV show that truly cares
about its audience,

23:16.522 --> 23:19.107
that loves and respects them, should...

23:19.107 --> 23:23.028
no... must be canceled every few years.

23:23.028 --> 23:25.948
It's simply the right thing to do.

23:25.948 --> 23:29.910
[applause]
[Hyper-Chicken clucking loudly]

23:29.910 --> 23:31.828
Thank you.
[applause stops]

23:35.207 --> 23:38.293
- Sobering thoughts from some
drug-addled weirdo.

23:38.293 --> 23:40.754
Goodnight, God bless Earth,

23:40.754 --> 23:42.256
and aroo.

23:42.256 --> 23:45.259
♪
